1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,482
Hello! Welcome to the world of Hangul, the easiest and most scientific alphabet in the world.

2
00:00:07,482 --> 00:00:13,091
In the early Joseon Dynasty, commoners who could not read faced many social disadvantages.

3
00:00:13,091 --> 00:00:18,764
Chinese characters were too complex to learn, making it impossible for ordinary people to gain knowledge.

4
00:00:18,764 --> 00:00:24,527
King Sejong, who pitied the suffering of his people, sought to create an easy, native writing system.

5
00:00:24,527 --> 00:00:30,509
Despite opposition from the ruling class who defended Chinese characters, Sejong continued his work in secret.

6
00:00:30,509 --> 00:00:37,227
Finally, in 1446, Hunminjeongeum, meaning 'the proper sounds for instructing the people', was promulgated.

7
00:00:37,227 --> 00:00:42,773
It embodies Sejong's love for the people, believing that writing should be easily used by everyone.

8
00:00:42,773 --> 00:00:48,864
Hangul is not just a phonetic alphabet; it is a featural alphabet where letter shapes reflect phonetic properties.

9
00:00:48,864 --> 00:00:54,818
A wise man can learn it in a morning, and even a simple man can learn it in ten days.

10
00:00:54,818 --> 00:01:00,600
Today, leading linguists worldwide praise Hangul as the most sophisticated writing system.

11
00:01:00,600 --> 00:01:06,445
Hangul's consonants mimic the actual shape of the vocal organs when producing sound.

12
00:01:06,445 --> 00:01:11,182
The consonant 'G [k/g]' represents the root of the tongue blocking the throat.

13
00:01:11,182 --> 00:01:16,373
The consonant 'N' depicts the tip of the tongue touching the upper gums.

14
00:01:16,373 --> 00:01:22,109
The consonant 'M' is the outline of the lips meeting to open and close sounds.

15
00:01:22,109 --> 00:01:27,800
The consonant 'S' represents the sharp shape of teeth where air friction is created.

16
00:01:27,800 --> 00:01:33,300
The consonant 'NG' mimics the circular cross-section of the open throat.

17
00:01:33,300 --> 00:01:38,691
Let's look at the structure of the 'G' sound when the tongue pulls back, narrowing the throat.

18
00:01:38,691 --> 00:01:44,036
Feel the blockage of air as the tongue tip taps the upper gums when making the 'N' sound.

19
00:01:44,036 --> 00:01:49,491
The comfortable bilabial movement of the 'M' sound, where lips close to gather sound and then release.

20
00:01:49,491 --> 00:01:54,682
The alveolar fricative 'S' sound, where the tongue tip rests slightly behind the lower teeth as air escapes.

21
00:01:54,682 --> 00:02:00,136
This is the 'principle of stroke addition', adding lines to base shapes as sounds become stronger.

22
00:02:00,136 --> 00:02:05,745
Adding a stroke to 'ㄱ' makes 'ㅋ', visually representing a stronger burst of air.

23
00:02:05,745 --> 00:02:11,264
Adding a stroke to 'ㄴ' makes 'ㄷ', and adding another makes 'ㅌ'.

24
00:02:11,264 --> 00:02:17,045
Extending strokes on 'ㅁ' creates 'ㅂ', and adding more horizontal strokes completes 'ㅍ'.

25
00:02:17,045 --> 00:02:22,827
Adding a top stroke to 'ㅅ' creates 'ㅈ', and another makes the aspirated 'ㅊ'.

26
00:02:22,827 --> 00:02:28,700
Adding strokes to 'ㅇ' forms 'ㅎ', representing strong breath passing through the throat.

27
00:02:28,700 --> 00:02:35,045
Writing two identical letters side-by-side forms a tense, double consonant (Tense Sound).

28
00:02:35,045 --> 00:02:43,118
ㄲ, ㄸ, ㅃ, ㅆ, and ㅉ are called double consonants, expressing tension in the larynx.

29
00:02:43,118 --> 00:02:49,055
Instead of adding regular strokes, the flowing liquid 'ㄹ' is created by curling the tongue.

30
00:02:49,055 --> 00:02:55,055
Thus, Hangul establishes a complete system of 19 consonants derived from the 5 base shapes.

31
00:02:55,055 --> 00:03:00,945
Vowels are structured differently, combining the three core cosmic elements: Sky, Earth, and Human.

32
00:03:00,945 --> 00:03:05,809
First is the round dot representing the sky, called 'Araea' (•).

33
00:03:05,809 --> 00:03:10,936
Second is the horizontal line representing the flat earth, 'EU' (ㅡ).

34
00:03:10,936 --> 00:03:15,845
Third is the vertical line representing a standing human, 'I' (ㅣ).

35
00:03:15,845 --> 00:03:21,609
When Sky, Human, and Earth meet and combine, the basic vowels of Hangul are born.

36
00:03:21,609 --> 00:03:26,864
If the sky (•) rises to the right of the human (ㅣ), it is 'A [a]'; to the left, it is 'EO [ʌ]'.

37
00:03:26,864 --> 00:03:32,118
If the sky rises above the earth (ㅡ), it is 'O [o]'; below the earth, it is 'U [u]'.

38
00:03:32,118 --> 00:03:37,791
The vowels 'ㅏ' and 'ㅗ', stretching outward and upward, are bright 'Yang' vowels.

39
00:03:37,791 --> 00:03:43,400
The vowels 'ㅓ' and 'ㅜ', drawing inward and downward, are deep, calm 'Yin' vowels.

40
00:03:43,400 --> 00:03:49,245
Sky, Earth, and Human harmonize to complete the four base pillars of Hangul vowels.

41
00:03:49,245 --> 00:03:55,136
Adding the sky element twice creates y-glide diphthongs.

42
00:03:55,136 --> 00:04:01,073
Adding it twice yields YA, YEO, YO, and YU, enriching the vowel spectrum.

43
00:04:01,073 --> 00:04:06,182
The vertical vowel 'I' merges with other vowels to create compound vowels.

44
00:04:06,182 --> 00:04:11,591
ㅏ and ㅣ form 'AE', while ㅓ and ㅣ form 'E'.

45
00:04:11,591 --> 00:04:16,936
The diphthongs YA and YEO combine with 'I' to form 'YAE' and 'YE'.

46
00:04:16,936 --> 00:04:22,609
Horizontal vowels (ㅗ, ㅜ) combine with vertical ones to make rounded diphthongs.

47
00:04:22,609 --> 00:04:28,045
O and A make 'WA'; U and EO make 'WO', flowing into double articulation.

48
00:04:28,045 --> 00:04:33,127
OE, WI, and even WAE and WE require rounding the lips and shifting the tongue.

49
00:04:33,127 --> 00:04:38,536
The seemingly complex combination of ㅡ and ㅣ, 'UI', is a harmonious single flow.

50
00:04:38,536 --> 00:04:44,473
Starting from just 3 base shapes, Hangul boasts a rich system of 21 vowels.

51
00:04:44,473 --> 00:04:50,645
Let's learn the subtle differences in air pressure and vocal cord tension among plain, aspirated, and tense sounds.

52
00:04:50,645 --> 00:04:56,164
'G' is a relaxed plain sound, releasing air very softly and lightly.

53
00:04:56,164 --> 00:05:01,418
'K' is an aspirated sound, forcefully expelling air from deep within.

54
00:05:01,418 --> 00:05:07,418
'KK' is a tense sound, compressing the vocal cords with almost no escaping air.

55
00:05:07,418 --> 00:05:13,373
You can feel the difference between plain 'G' and aspirated 'K' by putting your hand in front of your mouth.

56
00:05:13,373 --> 00:05:19,064
The contrast between plain 'G' and tense 'KK' is like the 'K' in 'key' versus 'sky'.

57
00:05:19,064 --> 00:05:24,300
Hold a thin sheet of paper; it should bend back dramatically only when you pronounce 'K'.

58
00:05:24,300 --> 00:05:29,864
When making the tense 'KK', pitch the following vowel higher and sharper.

59
00:05:29,864 --> 00:05:35,318
Tense and aspirated sounds should feel crisp, with a distinct staccato separation.

60
00:05:35,318 --> 00:05:43,155
Solidify the 3-step difference of G/K/KK, D/T/TT, and B/P/PP in your mind.

61
00:05:43,155 --> 00:05:48,127
Here is the precise articulation mechanism for the vowels that foreigners find hardest.

62
00:05:48,127 --> 00:05:53,473
To pronounce 'EU [ɯ]', stretch your lips wide to the sides as if smiling.

63
00:05:53,473 --> 00:05:59,100
Keep the lips flat and unrounded, raising only the back of your tongue.

64
00:05:59,100 --> 00:06:05,191
To pronounce 'EO [ʌ]', drop your jaw low while keeping your lips relaxed and flat.

65
00:06:05,191 --> 00:06:10,845
To pronounce 'O [o]', round your lips into a small, tight circle as if holding a straw.

66
00:06:10,845 --> 00:06:16,409
Compare the wide jaw of 'EO' versus the tight circular lips of 'O'.

67
00:06:16,409 --> 00:06:21,709
For 'U [u]', purse your lips even tighter than 'O' and project them forward.

68
00:06:21,709 --> 00:06:27,036
Spot the difference: the tiny, tense circle of 'U' versus the medium circle of 'O'.

69
00:06:27,036 --> 00:06:32,818
Check in a mirror to make sure your lips do not round when saying 'EO' and 'EU'.

70
00:06:32,818 --> 00:06:39,673
Fully master the combination of tongue height and lip rounding for EU, EO, O, and U.

71
00:06:39,673 --> 00:06:45,127
Instead of aligning letters side-by-side, Hangul groups them into syllable blocks.

72
00:06:45,127 --> 00:06:50,864
If the vowel has a vertical stroke (ㅣ), it sits to the right of the consonant.

73
00:06:50,864 --> 00:06:56,645
If the vowel has a horizontal stroke (ㅡ), it sits directly under the consonant.

74
00:06:56,645 --> 00:07:02,382
Vowels with both horizontal and vertical strokes wrap around the right and bottom of the consonant.

75
00:07:02,382 --> 00:07:08,073
The final consonant placed at the very bottom of a syllable is called 'Batchim'.

76
00:07:08,073 --> 00:07:13,682
A final consonant joins below, completing a 3-layered syllable like 'GANG'.

77
00:07:13,682 --> 00:07:19,636
Though many consonants can be written as Batchim, they are pronounced as only 7 sounds.

78
00:07:19,636 --> 00:07:28,055
The final consonants ㅅ, ㅆ, ㅈ, ㅊ, ㄷ, ㅌ, and ㅎ all collapse into the representative 'D [t]' sound.

79
00:07:28,055 --> 00:07:33,855
Batchim sounds are unreleased, stopping air flow abruptly inside the mouth.

80
00:07:33,855 --> 00:07:39,545
Sometimes double/complex Batchims appear, where only one consonant is voiced.

81
00:07:39,545 --> 00:07:45,000
When a Batchim is followed by an empty 'ㅇ', the sound links over to the next syllable.

82
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:50,364
'Babeul' is read as [ba-beul], and 'kkochi' as [kko-chi], flowing naturally.

83
00:07:50,364 --> 00:07:58,855
When G, D, B meet N or M, they shift to soft nasal sounds: NG, N, M.

84
00:07:58,855 --> 00:08:03,655
In 'Gamsahamnida', 'hap-ni' is pronounced as [ham-ni], making it smoother to say.

85
00:08:03,655 --> 00:08:09,655
When a final D or T meets the vowel 'I', it palatalizes into J or CH.

86
00:08:09,655 --> 00:08:15,782
Reading 'gudi' as [guji] and 'gati' as [gachi] is similar to 'would you' in English.

87
00:08:15,782 --> 00:08:21,127
When N and L meet, both assimilate into a smooth, liquid double 'L' sound.

88
00:08:21,127 --> 00:08:26,691
While English moves to stress-based rhythm, Korean flows flatly based on syllable blocks.

89
00:08:26,691 --> 00:08:32,382
Rather than chopping words apart, let them glide, riding the natural sound changes.

90
00:08:32,382 --> 00:08:38,909
Congratulations on mastering Hangul! Join our new learning journey with a subscribe and like!
